WEBVTT

00:05.875 --> 00:08.573
THOMAS P. BRADY:
The loveliest and the purest

00:08.704 --> 00:10.401
of God's creatures,

00:10.532 --> 00:13.100
the nearest thing to
an angelic being,

00:13.230 --> 00:15.624
is a well-bred Southern woman

00:15.754 --> 00:19.367
or her blue-eyed,
golden-haired little girl.

00:19.497 --> 00:22.413
This is why we can't put
little boys

00:22.544 --> 00:24.720
and little girls together,

00:24.850 --> 00:27.505
Negroes and whites,

00:27.636 --> 00:29.942
and have them sing together,

00:30.073 --> 00:34.643
play together,
dance together, eat together.

00:34.773 --> 00:38.951
You cannot do this
and then expect the sensitivity

00:39.082 --> 00:43.869
of those white children
not to be broken down.

00:44.000 --> 00:46.176
-[crowd shouting "no!"]
-You can't do it!

00:46.307 --> 00:50.311
By abolishing
school segregation,

00:50.441 --> 00:52.922
the Supreme Court has set aside

00:53.053 --> 00:57.535
all the laws of eugenics
and biology created by God.

00:59.929 --> 01:05.804
If trouble is to come, we can
predict how it will start--

01:05.935 --> 01:10.331
the glib young Negro
who sojourned in Chicago

01:10.461 --> 01:13.812
or New York
will perform an obscene act,

01:13.943 --> 01:15.988
or make an obscene remark,

01:16.119 --> 01:22.169
or assault on some white girl,
for they will reason,

01:22.299 --> 01:26.173
"Has not the Supreme Court
abolished segregation?

01:26.303 --> 01:27.609
Would the federal government

01:27.739 --> 01:29.915
-not protect us?"
-[crowd shouting "no!"]

01:30.046 --> 01:34.833
This is the reasoning
which produces riots

01:34.964 --> 01:39.360
and bloodshed,
raping, and revolutions.

01:39.490 --> 01:43.277
[cheers and applause]

01:43.407 --> 01:45.540
♪♪

01:45.670 --> 01:48.847
[indistinct conversations]

01:48.978 --> 01:51.807
[solemn music plays]

01:51.937 --> 01:58.814
♪♪

01:58.944 --> 02:05.821
♪♪

02:05.951 --> 02:12.523
♪♪

02:12.654 --> 02:14.438
♪♪

02:14.569 --> 02:17.049
We'll begin closing arguments
momentarily.

02:17.180 --> 02:18.790
How many do you think
they turned?

02:18.921 --> 02:20.749
At this point,
does it even matter?

02:20.879 --> 02:22.968
You're damn right it does.
The defense played dirty.

02:23.099 --> 02:25.623
They knew that
if the judge let Carolyn

02:25.754 --> 02:27.712
take the stand,
her story would get to the jury.

02:27.843 --> 02:29.845
It didn't matter if he ruled it
inadmissible or not.

02:29.975 --> 02:31.673
Well, what'd you expect?

02:31.803 --> 02:34.980
Everyone knows Breland ranks
high in the Citizens' Council.

02:38.549 --> 02:40.899
Well, it's not like
I haven't seen one before,

02:41.030 --> 02:43.641
but burning crosses
usually aren't directed at folks

02:43.772 --> 02:46.470
-who look like us.
-Hmph.

02:46.601 --> 02:47.689
[sighs]

02:47.819 --> 02:49.647
What happened there?

02:49.778 --> 02:51.823
-Sunburn.
-I see that.

02:51.954 --> 02:53.085
What's the story?

02:53.216 --> 02:56.045
I was following up on a lead.

02:58.003 --> 03:00.919
I'd heard that, uh,
those two Negro witnesses

03:01.050 --> 03:02.704
were being held
in the Charleston jail

03:02.834 --> 03:05.663
for the duration of the trial.

03:05.794 --> 03:06.925
Where'd you hear that?

03:07.056 --> 03:09.145
I can't reveal my sources,

03:09.276 --> 03:13.323
but I asked those deputies
for directions to sniff it out.

03:13.454 --> 03:15.760
Instead of directions,
they offered me a ride.

03:15.891 --> 03:17.762
Turns out
it was a one-way fare,

03:17.893 --> 03:19.460
and I was stuck
walking five miles

03:19.590 --> 03:21.636
in the midday sun
back into town.

03:21.766 --> 03:23.725
[chuckles]

03:23.855 --> 03:25.074
You're lucky
they didn't do more

03:25.205 --> 03:26.380
than leave your ass
in the country.

03:26.510 --> 03:28.643
[sighs] Very true.

03:32.386 --> 03:34.823
RUBY: Mamie, we thought
you'd left town.

03:34.953 --> 03:38.000
I nearly did.

03:38.130 --> 03:41.569
I, um--
I bit my tongue yesterday

03:41.699 --> 03:44.354
while that woman lied
about my son,

03:44.485 --> 03:46.704
and I just couldn't
bring myself to sit

03:46.835 --> 03:48.750
through the parade of character
witnesses this morning.

03:48.880 --> 03:50.360
All you missed were
a bunch of peckerwoods

03:50.491 --> 03:52.797
trying to convince us
that Bryant and Milam

03:52.928 --> 03:55.235
had "the best reputations
two men could ever have."

03:55.365 --> 03:57.149
I figured.

03:57.280 --> 03:59.717
You know, as much as I wanted
to pack up

03:59.848 --> 04:02.764
and put this nightmare
behind me,

04:02.894 --> 04:06.202
I remembered what you said
about showing up.

04:06.333 --> 04:09.205
So... here I am.

04:09.336 --> 04:12.382
[indistinct conversations]

04:13.688 --> 04:17.039
I don't want that woman
thinking I bought

04:17.169 --> 04:19.302
any of that garbage
she spewed up there,

04:19.433 --> 04:22.392
but if I had left, she might've.

04:22.523 --> 04:25.395
[tense music plays]

04:25.526 --> 04:31.662
♪♪

04:31.793 --> 04:33.098
[gavel bangs]

04:33.229 --> 04:34.491
JUDGE SWANGO:
Order in the court.

04:34.926 --> 04:37.189
Gentlemen, are you prepared
to give your closing arguments?

04:37.320 --> 04:38.582
BRELAND:
Yes, Your Honor.

04:38.713 --> 04:41.281
The state may begin.

04:41.411 --> 04:44.849
CHATHAM: There's been a lot of
talk about this case

04:44.980 --> 04:47.896
inside this courtroom
and out,

04:48.026 --> 04:49.158
but I'm not concerned

04:49.332 --> 04:52.292
with outside organizations'
interference.

04:52.422 --> 04:57.340
My only concern is what
is morally right or wrong.

04:57.471 --> 05:00.300
And if you return a verdict
based on anything other

05:00.430 --> 05:03.477
than the evidence presented
to you in this courtroom,

05:03.607 --> 05:06.480
then you will endanger
every custom

05:06.610 --> 05:09.613
and tradition
the South holds dear.

05:09.744 --> 05:14.270
And we all know
that a true Southerner

05:14.401 --> 05:17.229
would never kill a child.

05:17.360 --> 05:20.276
I was born and bred
in the South,

05:20.407 --> 05:23.801
and if Emmett Till acted up
and deserved to be punished,

05:23.932 --> 05:25.542
like the defense
would have you believe,

05:25.673 --> 05:29.241
then the worst punishment
that should've occurred

05:29.372 --> 05:31.243
was a whipping.

05:31.374 --> 05:37.598
Because down here, we deal
with a child as a child,

05:37.728 --> 05:41.123
not as a man.

05:41.253 --> 05:45.693
♪♪

05:45.823 --> 05:49.958
The fact remains the very first
words of the state's testimony

05:50.088 --> 05:53.701
were dripping with
the blood of a child.

05:53.831 --> 05:56.356
And what were those words,
gentlemen?

05:58.575 --> 06:02.753
They were "Preacher, preacher.

06:02.884 --> 06:06.148
I want that boy from Chicago--

06:06.278 --> 06:09.804
the boy that did
the talking in Money."

06:09.934 --> 06:16.288
♪♪

06:16.419 --> 06:18.856
[telephones ringing]

06:18.987 --> 06:23.513
I've come to collect my--
my witness fee, sir.

06:23.644 --> 06:24.775
Mose Wright's my name.

06:24.906 --> 06:27.082
I know who you are.

06:30.172 --> 06:32.000
[suspenseful music plays]

06:32.130 --> 06:37.919
♪♪

06:38.049 --> 06:40.574
[money rustling]

06:40.704 --> 06:47.407
♪♪

06:47.537 --> 06:48.669
♪♪

06:48.799 --> 06:52.150
[indistinct conversations
in distance]

06:52.281 --> 06:58.026
♪♪

06:58.156 --> 07:03.988
♪♪

07:04.119 --> 07:05.207
[flashbulb pops]

07:05.337 --> 07:07.383
-Mr. Wright. Sir.
-Mose. Mose.

07:07.514 --> 07:08.645
Can we get a question
from you, sir?

07:08.776 --> 07:10.386
Any comment, sir?

07:10.517 --> 07:12.214
♪♪

07:12.344 --> 07:14.216
Where you going, Preacher?

07:14.346 --> 07:17.785
♪♪

07:17.915 --> 07:20.570
[flashbulb pops]

07:20.701 --> 07:26.446
♪♪

07:26.576 --> 07:32.408
♪♪

07:32.539 --> 07:34.323
CHATHAM: Now we have
this doctor come up here,

07:34.454 --> 07:37.848
with his degrees and titles,
and he says that he cannot tell

07:37.979 --> 07:40.372
whether the body
was white or colored.

07:40.503 --> 07:44.159
Now, if a doctor cannot tell
a Black body from white,

07:44.289 --> 07:46.814
I sure don't want him writing
any prescriptions for me.

07:46.944 --> 07:49.730
[crowd laughs]

07:51.558 --> 07:57.041
All it took was someone
who knew and loved Emmett Till

07:57.172 --> 08:00.697
to identify him,
not a doctor or a sheriff.

08:03.134 --> 08:06.790
If there was anything
left of Emmett Till--

08:06.921 --> 08:11.403
a hairline, an ear,
or just part of a nose--

08:11.534 --> 08:15.973
then I say to you
that his mother, Mamie Bradley,

08:16.104 --> 08:19.803
was God's given witness
to identify him.

08:19.934 --> 08:23.024
[dramatic music plays]

08:23.154 --> 08:29.291
♪♪

08:29.421 --> 08:30.858
[chair slides]

08:30.988 --> 08:35.950
♪♪

08:36.080 --> 08:37.473
BRELAND:
Now, in order to, uh,

08:37.647 --> 08:41.477
convict these young men of
murder in the first degree,

08:41.608 --> 08:45.089
each of you has to be convinced,

08:45.220 --> 08:47.614
beyond a reasonable doubt
and moral certainty,

08:47.744 --> 08:50.181
that the state
has proven their guilt.

08:51.705 --> 08:56.013
The state has proven nothing,
and certainly not murder.

08:56.144 --> 09:00.452
Eh, suppose J.W. Milam
and Roy Bryant

09:00.583 --> 09:04.456
did take Emmett Till
and later turned him loose.

09:04.587 --> 09:07.764
Suppose old Mose got in his car

09:07.895 --> 09:12.421
and found the boy along the road
as he walked home.

09:12.552 --> 09:18.079
Mose may have taken him
to meet a friend,

09:18.209 --> 09:20.342
involved with people
who want to, uh,

09:20.472 --> 09:23.519
defy the customs of the South--

09:23.650 --> 09:28.480
people who may have persuaded
Mose to take Emmett Till's ring

09:28.611 --> 09:30.482
and put it on a rotten,
stinking corpse

09:30.613 --> 09:33.224
that could later be found
floating in the river.

09:34.748 --> 09:40.667
Now, when you, uh, walk into
that room to deliberate,

09:40.797 --> 09:43.583
I want you to think
about your future.

09:45.236 --> 09:48.936
'Cause when your summons comes
to cross the Great Divide,

09:49.066 --> 09:50.807
and as you enter
your father's house--

09:50.938 --> 09:53.723
a home not made by human hands,
but eternal in the heavens--

09:53.854 --> 09:56.552
you can look back to where
your father's feet have trod

09:56.683 --> 09:59.250
and see your good record
written in the sands of time,

09:59.381 --> 10:03.167
and when you go down
to your lonely, silent tomb

10:03.298 --> 10:04.952
to a sleep that knows no dreams,

10:05.082 --> 10:07.171
I want you to hold
in the palm of your hand

10:07.302 --> 10:10.566
a record of service to God
and your fellow man.

10:10.697 --> 10:13.134
[tense music plays]

10:13.264 --> 10:18.530
And the only way you can do that
is to turn these boys loose.

10:18.661 --> 10:20.707
Every last Anglo-Saxon
one of you

10:20.837 --> 10:24.145
has the courage
to free these men.

10:24.275 --> 10:30.368
♪♪

10:30.499 --> 10:36.636
♪♪

10:36.766 --> 10:38.986
Has the defense completed
their closing arguments?

10:39.116 --> 10:40.814
Your Honor, we have.

10:41.989 --> 10:43.599
JUDGE SWANGO: The state has
the option of delivering

10:43.730 --> 10:46.820
the final word to the jury,
if you choose to take it.

10:46.950 --> 10:51.041
♪♪

10:51.172 --> 10:53.391
Does the state have
anything else to offer?

10:53.522 --> 10:55.959
♪♪

10:56.090 --> 10:58.527
Yes, Your Honor. We do.

10:58.658 --> 11:01.269
♪♪

11:01.399 --> 11:05.447
What you just heard is
the most far-fetched argument

11:05.577 --> 11:08.711
ever uttered in a courtroom.

11:08.842 --> 11:12.497
Mose Wright didn't
help stage a murder.

11:13.890 --> 11:15.805
It's simple.

11:15.936 --> 11:18.939
The defendants took the law
into their own hands

11:19.069 --> 11:20.462
and gave that boy
a court-martial

11:20.592 --> 11:22.290
with the death penalty imposed

11:22.420 --> 11:27.643
because they didn't think anyone
had the courage to come forward

11:27.774 --> 11:29.645
and do what was morally right.

11:30.951 --> 11:35.477
I am asking you to find that
courage within yourselves today,

11:35.607 --> 11:39.002
because the defense
is right about one thing--

11:39.133 --> 11:41.309
there are outside agitators

11:41.439 --> 11:44.791
trying to destroy
our Southern way of life,

11:44.921 --> 11:48.185
but once we take
the life, liberty,

11:48.316 --> 11:51.362
and pursuit of happiness
from anyone,

11:51.493 --> 11:54.061
we will be put on the defensive

11:54.191 --> 11:58.674
and become vulnerable
in justifying our stand.

11:58.805 --> 12:05.289
Only so long as we can help
preserve the rights of everyone,

12:05.420 --> 12:08.466
White or Black,

12:08.597 --> 12:12.644
can we keep our way of life.

12:12.775 --> 12:18.215
♪♪

12:18.346 --> 12:20.087
♪♪

12:21.175 --> 12:24.265
[indistinct conversations]

12:24.395 --> 12:27.050
[tense music plays]

12:27.703 --> 12:30.053
[sighs] So, what now?

12:30.184 --> 12:31.533
We just sit here and wait?

12:31.663 --> 12:33.230
[sighs]
That's all we really can do.

12:33.361 --> 12:36.103
Y-Yes, of course, but in here?

12:36.233 --> 12:37.713
With this humidity?
[breathing heavily]

12:37.844 --> 12:39.628
I mean, I-I can
hardly breathe.

12:39.759 --> 12:41.108
If we leave now,
we're gon' lose our seats.

12:41.238 --> 12:43.110
-HICKS: All right.
-[paper tears]

12:43.240 --> 12:46.243
Write down your name
and a number.

12:46.374 --> 12:48.724
-And what is he doing?
-RUBY: Being an ass.

12:48.855 --> 12:50.726
Making wagers.

12:50.857 --> 12:52.597
Predicting how long
it's gonna take.

12:52.728 --> 12:53.947
To deliberate?

12:54.077 --> 12:55.209
And acquit.

12:55.339 --> 13:01.998
♪♪

13:02.129 --> 13:08.744
♪♪

13:08.875 --> 13:14.532
♪♪

13:14.663 --> 13:17.361
Everyone's expecting this
to wrap up soon, aren't they?

13:17.492 --> 13:19.320
A quick verdict doesn't
necessarily mean

13:19.450 --> 13:20.451
it won't go our way.

13:20.582 --> 13:22.192
[door opens]

13:22.323 --> 13:27.154
♪♪

13:27.284 --> 13:28.633
They're not done.

13:28.764 --> 13:30.200
They're thirsty.

13:30.331 --> 13:33.073
[laughter]

13:33.203 --> 13:34.465
Well, let's get 'em some Cokes.

13:34.596 --> 13:36.685
[laughter continues]

13:38.426 --> 13:42.473
Wait, this is a joke
to these people, isn't it?

13:42.604 --> 13:43.866
[laughter subsides]

13:43.997 --> 13:49.089
♪♪

13:49.219 --> 13:51.395
JUROR:
Ten not guilty.

13:51.526 --> 13:53.920
Two abstained.

13:54.050 --> 13:56.487
Looks like two of y'all
are trying to hang us.

13:57.619 --> 14:00.796
Guess we gotta sort some
things out before we vote again.

14:00.927 --> 14:02.754
All right.

14:02.885 --> 14:04.800
According to them undertakers,

14:04.931 --> 14:08.673
that body had hair on its chest.

14:08.804 --> 14:11.459
Blacks don't grow hair
on their chest till they're 30,

14:11.589 --> 14:13.983
so there ain't no way
the body was that boy's.

14:14.114 --> 14:15.593
Eh, now wait a second.

14:15.724 --> 14:18.074
[stammers] That boy's mother
identified the body.

14:18.205 --> 14:19.771
That body didn't look
like nobody.

14:19.902 --> 14:21.599
Eh, it would be pretty hard
for a mother

14:21.730 --> 14:23.123
to make a mistake
about her own child.

14:23.253 --> 14:25.342
JUROR #2: Eh, I didn't buy
a word she said.

14:25.473 --> 14:26.822
And if she tried
a little harder,

14:26.953 --> 14:28.563
she might have squeezed out
a few more tears,

14:28.693 --> 14:30.521
don't you think?

14:30.652 --> 14:32.567
Milam and Bryant
confessed to taking the boy.

14:32.697 --> 14:34.351
They let him go,

14:34.482 --> 14:37.006
and what happened to him after
hasn't been proven by the state.

14:37.137 --> 14:38.573
Well, those farmhands--

14:38.703 --> 14:40.923
they saw him on the way
to the Milam property.

14:41.054 --> 14:42.011
They-- They--
They heard his screams.

14:42.403 --> 14:43.883
And you heard what happened
in that market.

14:44.013 --> 14:46.755
Now, what if it had been
your wife or your sister,

14:46.886 --> 14:49.105
all alone when that brute
strutted in there,

14:49.236 --> 14:50.541
smart-talking her,

14:50.715 --> 14:53.283
thinking he could come down here
and do as he pleased?

14:53.414 --> 14:56.504
♪♪

14:56.634 --> 14:59.463
What we do today
means something.

14:59.594 --> 15:01.944
It'll either put folks
on notice,

15:02.075 --> 15:05.252
or give 'em permission to do
whatever the hell they please

15:05.382 --> 15:08.124
the next time the opportunity
presents itself.

15:08.255 --> 15:14.914
♪♪

15:15.044 --> 15:17.394
[papers rustle]

15:17.525 --> 15:23.705
♪♪

15:23.835 --> 15:29.102
♪♪

15:29.232 --> 15:30.538
[knock on door]

15:30.668 --> 15:32.018
[door opens]

15:32.148 --> 15:35.195
♪♪

15:35.325 --> 15:38.502
[crowd murmuring]

15:38.633 --> 15:42.071
♪♪

15:42.202 --> 15:43.812
Let the courtroom be in order.

15:43.943 --> 15:49.035
♪♪

15:49.165 --> 15:50.688
Have you gentlemen
reached a verdict?

15:50.819 --> 15:51.994
Yes.

15:52.125 --> 15:53.169
Has your verdict been made
in accordance

15:53.300 --> 15:54.518
with the form
that was given to you?

15:54.649 --> 15:55.606
Yes.

15:55.867 --> 15:57.652
Please give the verdict
to the clerk.

15:57.782 --> 16:04.615
♪♪

16:04.746 --> 16:06.226
♪♪

16:06.356 --> 16:10.317
For the charge of murder,
we the jury find the defendants,

16:10.447 --> 16:13.363
Roy Bryant and J.W. Milam...

16:13.494 --> 16:16.323
♪ I love my baby

16:16.453 --> 16:18.542
♪ With all my might

16:18.673 --> 16:20.544
REPORTER:
We're broadcasting live outside

16:20.675 --> 16:22.590
of the Tallahatchie
County courthouse.

16:22.720 --> 16:25.375
The murder trial against
J.W. Milam and Roy Bryant,

16:25.506 --> 16:29.075
the two men accused of killing
14-year-old Negro Emmett Till,

16:29.205 --> 16:30.728
has come to an end.

16:30.859 --> 16:33.079
After 67 minutes
of deliberation,

16:33.209 --> 16:35.820
the jury has reached
a verdict--

16:37.997 --> 16:39.346
not guilty.

16:39.476 --> 16:42.131
[cheers and applause]

16:42.262 --> 16:44.916
[horns honking]

16:45.047 --> 16:46.309
[click, radio shuts off]

16:49.095 --> 16:51.619
67 minutes.

16:51.749 --> 16:53.403
It was all show.

16:53.534 --> 16:54.709
They threw us a bone.

16:55.057 --> 16:57.712
They gave us a trial
because the world was watching,

16:57.842 --> 17:00.628
and they will claim
that they gave us a fair shot,

17:00.758 --> 17:01.846
and that the state
of Mississippi did

17:02.325 --> 17:04.545
all that they could do,
and the world will believe it.

17:04.675 --> 17:06.721
Unless we tell them otherwise.

17:06.851 --> 17:08.462
Unless we tell the truth.

17:08.592 --> 17:10.377
I have no doubt that you will.

17:11.639 --> 17:13.206
I said "we."

17:15.034 --> 17:17.384
If Leflore County prosecutes
on kidnapping charges,

17:17.514 --> 17:19.386
we could have
another trial ahead of us.

17:19.516 --> 17:22.258
How do we pressure them
to make sure they do prosecute?

17:22.389 --> 17:24.130
Invitations for you to speak
started coming in

17:24.260 --> 17:26.784
the moment you stepped off
that stage in Chicago.

17:26.915 --> 17:28.438
I didn't think it was
appropriate to bother you

17:28.569 --> 17:30.266
with all that business
during the trial,

17:30.397 --> 17:32.660
but now that it's over,

17:32.790 --> 17:34.140
what do you think
about getting out there

17:34.270 --> 17:36.838
and telling folks
what really went on down here?

17:36.968 --> 17:39.232
[somber music plays]

17:39.362 --> 17:42.278
I let people see
what they did to Emmett.

17:44.324 --> 17:46.456
Now it's time to tell them.

17:46.587 --> 17:52.419
♪♪

17:52.549 --> 17:53.898
♪♪

17:54.029 --> 17:56.379
I realize it's been
quite a stressful day,

17:56.510 --> 17:59.817
so I appreciate your time
in speaking with us.

17:59.948 --> 18:02.385
[indistinct conversations]

18:02.516 --> 18:04.648
So, how do you folks feel
now that it's all over?

18:04.779 --> 18:06.607
Roy, how about you?

18:06.737 --> 18:08.696
I'm just glad it's over with.

18:08.826 --> 18:10.001
J.W.?

18:10.132 --> 18:11.220
I am, too.

18:11.351 --> 18:12.482
Mrs. Bryant? Uh...

18:12.613 --> 18:14.093
I'm fine.

18:14.223 --> 18:16.530
-And how about you, Mrs. Milam?
-JUANITA: Fine.

18:16.660 --> 18:17.792
What happens next for you folks?

18:17.922 --> 18:19.098
What's on the docket?

18:19.228 --> 18:21.448
I haven't decided yet.
I don't know yet.

18:21.578 --> 18:23.319
REPORTER: Roy, will you open
your store again?

18:24.538 --> 18:26.061
I don't know.

18:26.192 --> 18:27.628
The eyes of a lot of people
have been on you

18:27.758 --> 18:28.803
these last few days,

18:29.064 --> 18:30.935
and now you're free
of this murder charge.

18:31.066 --> 18:33.112
There's still
the kidnapping charge

18:33.242 --> 18:34.200
that has to be
taken care of, too.

18:34.330 --> 18:36.115
Is that right?

18:36.245 --> 18:37.855
I don't know.
If you want anything else,

18:37.986 --> 18:39.596
you'll have to
talk to our lawyers.

18:39.727 --> 18:41.685
Now, if you'll excuse us.

18:41.816 --> 18:43.731
[giggles]

18:44.949 --> 18:47.169
[flashbulbs pop]

18:47.300 --> 18:49.432
[film reel clicking]

18:49.563 --> 18:51.130
[flashbulb pops]

18:51.260 --> 18:53.610
I need you fellas
to come with me.

18:54.785 --> 18:56.918
What?
Where are you taking them?

18:57.048 --> 18:59.616
Leflore County. For processing.

18:59.747 --> 19:06.580
♪♪

19:06.710 --> 19:08.843
All right, make room, make room.

19:08.973 --> 19:10.627
Y'all back off. Back off there.

19:10.758 --> 19:11.846
SHERIFF SMITH:
Afternoon.

19:11.976 --> 19:15.110
J.W. Milam, Roy Bryant,

19:15.241 --> 19:17.895
you're under arrest for
the kidnapping of Emmett Till.

19:18.026 --> 19:19.419
[flashbulb pops]

19:19.549 --> 19:24.250
♪♪

19:24.380 --> 19:26.252
[handcuffs click]

19:26.382 --> 19:27.601
We'll be out in no time.

19:27.731 --> 19:29.559
[handcuffs click]

19:29.690 --> 19:32.736
♪♪

19:32.867 --> 19:34.303
George.

19:34.434 --> 19:36.349
[sighs]

19:36.479 --> 19:38.742
Folks are tired, George.

19:38.873 --> 19:40.788
They're ready for this circus
to leave town.

19:40.918 --> 19:43.138
You drag this kidnapping
nonsense on too long,

19:43.269 --> 19:44.705
they'll grow tired of you, too.

19:44.835 --> 19:46.968
I'm gonna do the job
I was elected to do

19:47.098 --> 19:49.057
for as long as
I'm in the Sheriff's Office.

19:49.188 --> 19:51.407
It might serve you well
to do the same.

19:51.538 --> 19:55.106
♪♪

19:55.237 --> 19:56.934
Let's get the hell out of here.

19:57.065 --> 19:58.719
[engine starts]

19:58.849 --> 20:03.811
♪♪

20:03.941 --> 20:08.990
♪♪

20:11.253 --> 20:13.516
[vehicle approaches]

20:13.647 --> 20:15.562
[horn honks]

20:17.303 --> 20:19.348
[brakes squeak]

20:19.479 --> 20:20.567
[sighs]

20:22.177 --> 20:23.352
Come on, Dallas.

20:26.573 --> 20:27.617
[grunts]

20:27.748 --> 20:29.315
It's time.

20:29.793 --> 20:31.142
[clang]

20:32.622 --> 20:33.797
[door opens]

20:33.928 --> 20:35.016
Come on.

20:36.626 --> 20:38.237
Come on.

20:39.629 --> 20:41.631
-Morning, Paul.
-Morning.

20:41.762 --> 20:43.372
You sure
you're ready to do this?

20:43.503 --> 20:45.983
Yeah. I don't have
much choice, do I?

20:46.114 --> 20:47.420
See, that's where you're wrong.

20:47.550 --> 20:49.204
You made a living down here.

20:49.335 --> 20:52.163
You have a little something left
over every month, don't you?

20:53.426 --> 20:55.776
There's not many of us
that can say that.

20:55.906 --> 20:57.734
Surely
things'll calm down soon.

20:57.865 --> 21:00.215
Now there's
a kidnapping trial.

21:00.346 --> 21:02.043
If there is, won't they
want you to testify?

21:02.173 --> 21:04.045
They will,
and I'll come back to do it,

21:04.175 --> 21:05.612
but I won't be staying.

21:06.569 --> 21:08.267
Suppose things won't be
getting back to normal

21:08.397 --> 21:10.007
around here anytime soon.

21:10.138 --> 21:12.140
Not for me and my boys,
it won't.

21:14.098 --> 21:15.970
Not for any of us.

21:17.624 --> 21:19.278
What's that?

21:19.408 --> 21:22.759
Oh, it's--
it's some dog chow.

21:22.890 --> 21:24.935
Some old dried bones.

21:25.066 --> 21:26.589
You gon' be
a tough act to follow,

21:26.720 --> 21:28.069
Mose Wright.

21:28.199 --> 21:29.375
You done spoiled this animal.

21:29.505 --> 21:30.637
Yeah.

21:30.767 --> 21:33.379
He's the best dog
in seven states.

21:33.509 --> 21:34.597
Mm-hmm.

21:36.164 --> 21:37.426
Hey.

21:37.557 --> 21:40.255
There you go. There you go.

21:40.386 --> 21:43.519
[uplifting music plays]

21:43.650 --> 21:45.913
You take care of him.

21:47.871 --> 21:49.612
Go on home with Paul, okay?

21:49.743 --> 21:51.701
That's Paul.
You're going home with him.

21:51.832 --> 21:52.963
You got it?

21:53.094 --> 21:55.401
All right. Come on. Get going.

21:55.531 --> 21:57.054
♪♪

21:57.185 --> 21:58.621
Go on.

21:58.752 --> 22:01.015
[Dallas whimpers]

22:02.190 --> 22:04.584
It took guts to get up there
on the stand.

22:04.714 --> 22:06.237
♪♪

22:06.368 --> 22:07.761
You know what else?

22:08.849 --> 22:10.590
Leaving takes guts, too.

22:10.720 --> 22:17.597
♪♪

22:17.727 --> 22:24.647
♪♪

22:24.778 --> 22:26.475
♪♪

22:26.606 --> 22:28.695
[door opens]

22:28.825 --> 22:31.480
PAUL: Get over there, boy.
Go on now.

22:31.611 --> 22:33.134
[door closes]

22:33.264 --> 22:35.919
There you go. Go on. Go on.

22:36.050 --> 22:37.704
[engine starts]

22:37.834 --> 22:44.667
♪♪

22:44.798 --> 22:51.674
♪♪

22:51.805 --> 22:58.681
♪♪

22:58.812 --> 23:05.732
♪♪

23:05.862 --> 23:11.868
♪♪

23:11.999 --> 23:13.174
♪♪

23:13.304 --> 23:14.567
[sighs]

23:14.697 --> 23:21.574
♪♪

23:21.704 --> 23:23.576
♪♪

23:24.968 --> 23:28.407
[indistinct conversations]

23:28.537 --> 23:30.496
[train horn honks]

23:30.626 --> 23:31.932
Daddy!

23:32.062 --> 23:33.542
Hey, son!

23:33.673 --> 23:35.762
[chuckling] Hey, boy. Hey.

23:35.892 --> 23:38.329
[laughs] Hi.

23:38.460 --> 23:40.593
Maurice. Gimme that.
Gimme that. Let me. I got it.

23:40.723 --> 23:42.072
[grunting] I got it.

23:43.857 --> 23:46.381
Put it up here. All right.

23:46.512 --> 23:49.384
Good to see you. [laughs]

23:49.515 --> 23:52.169
So, you excited to see Chicago?

23:52.300 --> 23:53.562
And Mama.

23:53.693 --> 23:55.434
I can't wait to see
Lincoln Park.

23:55.564 --> 23:57.784
What you know
about Lincoln Park?

23:57.914 --> 23:59.612
Bobo told me all about it.

24:01.309 --> 24:03.006
He did?

24:03.050 --> 24:06.183
[somber music plays]

24:06.314 --> 24:12.538
♪♪

24:12.668 --> 24:13.974
♪♪

24:14.104 --> 24:15.279
What'd he say?

24:15.410 --> 24:17.020
That Chicago summers
were the best.

24:17.151 --> 24:18.457
Hmm.

24:19.458 --> 24:22.678
[snorts, laughs]

24:24.898 --> 24:26.290
Yeah.

24:27.509 --> 24:29.163
You'll see.

24:29.293 --> 24:35.778
♪♪

24:35.909 --> 24:42.437
♪♪

24:42.568 --> 24:49.009
♪♪

24:49.139 --> 24:52.969
[brakes screech]

24:53.100 --> 24:55.232
[bell dinging]

24:55.363 --> 24:57.670
[gentle music plays]

24:57.800 --> 25:00.803
♪♪

25:00.934 --> 25:03.110
[indistinct conversations]

25:04.328 --> 25:06.113
MAURICE, ROBERT, SIMEON: Mama!

25:06.243 --> 25:13.120
♪♪

25:13.250 --> 25:20.127
♪♪

25:20.257 --> 25:26.829
♪♪

25:26.960 --> 25:33.793
♪♪

25:33.923 --> 25:40.800
♪♪

25:40.930 --> 25:43.106
♪♪

25:44.891 --> 25:46.849
MAMIE: What I saw
in that courtroom

25:46.980 --> 25:50.418
was a shame before God and man.

25:50.549 --> 25:53.813
It's about the biggest farce
I have ever seen.

25:53.943 --> 25:56.685
They claim to have
their own culture

25:56.816 --> 26:00.515
based on traditions
and institutions.

26:00.646 --> 26:02.343
They claim that they are
no different

26:02.473 --> 26:04.127
than other people
in this country,

26:04.258 --> 26:07.087
and I tell you that is a lie!

26:07.217 --> 26:10.351
[cheers and applause]

26:13.397 --> 26:16.879
My son didn't attack that woman.

26:17.010 --> 26:18.315
MAN: No.

26:18.446 --> 26:20.535
He was just a boy.

26:20.666 --> 26:27.542
♪♪

26:27.673 --> 26:29.718
♪♪

26:29.849 --> 26:33.592
And he paid a debt
for a lot of people.

26:36.638 --> 26:39.510
But I don't feel
that he is my child anymore.

26:39.641 --> 26:43.732
A little bit of him belongs
to everybody now,

26:43.863 --> 26:47.606
so it is up to all of us
to do our part.

26:47.736 --> 26:50.957
[cheers and applause]

26:51.087 --> 26:57.964
♪♪

26:58.094 --> 27:04.884
♪♪

27:05.014 --> 27:09.540
♪♪

27:09.671 --> 27:11.020
Ah.

27:12.674 --> 27:14.023
Welcome to Harlem.

27:14.154 --> 27:16.678
Mr. Wilkins,
thank you so much for coming.

27:16.809 --> 27:18.158
Of course.

27:18.288 --> 27:21.117
I must say, I have never seen
anything like that,

27:21.248 --> 27:25.165
certainly not with a woman
at the microphone.

27:25.295 --> 27:27.384
But first and foremost,
I am sorry that the trial

27:27.515 --> 27:28.734
did not go our way.

27:28.864 --> 27:30.605
Thank you.

27:30.736 --> 27:32.781
RAYFIELD: The good news is
the verdict is on the front page

27:32.912 --> 27:34.174
of every newspaper
in the country,

27:34.304 --> 27:36.132
and that means
every potential member

27:36.263 --> 27:38.918
of the next grand jury
is already following the story.

27:39.048 --> 27:40.963
I think it's time
we took control

27:41.094 --> 27:42.661
of the narrative,
don't you think?

27:42.791 --> 27:44.140
Absolutely.

27:44.271 --> 27:45.751
And we'd like to do just that,

27:45.881 --> 27:47.970
by offering you
an exclusive speaking tour,

27:48.101 --> 27:51.234
sponsored by the NAACP.

27:51.365 --> 27:52.758
If you'll have us.

27:52.888 --> 27:54.063
-I'd be honored.
-[chuckles]

27:54.194 --> 27:55.674
Isn't that wonderful, Rayfield?

27:55.804 --> 27:58.241
Yes, of course.

27:58.372 --> 28:02.637
But with all due respect,
as Mamie's advisor,

28:02.768 --> 28:05.031
I would ask that you give her
time to talk to a lawyer--

28:05.161 --> 28:07.903
one who isn't affiliated
with the NAACP--

28:08.034 --> 28:10.079
to make sure she's aware
of her options.

28:10.210 --> 28:11.864
As you know, there are many.

28:11.994 --> 28:14.431
Until you've settled on terms
with the NAACP,

28:14.562 --> 28:16.172
you have the freedom
to speak wherever you choose,

28:16.303 --> 28:18.131
but we will need
an answer soon,

28:18.261 --> 28:21.612
because the demand is only gonna
grow with each passing day,

28:21.743 --> 28:23.789
especially if you keep
delivering like you did today.

28:23.919 --> 28:25.442
[chuckles] Well, I have faith

28:25.573 --> 28:28.750
we will come to an agreement
we're all happy with.

28:28.881 --> 28:31.710
Until then,
I'm gonna keep talking.

28:31.840 --> 28:34.364
Good.
Because people are listening.

28:34.495 --> 28:35.844
[applause]

28:35.975 --> 28:37.193
Come with me.

28:43.025 --> 28:45.680
[door squeaks]

28:45.811 --> 28:48.683
[cheers and applause]

28:48.814 --> 28:50.729
[flashbulb pops]

28:55.559 --> 28:57.170
[flashbulb pops]

29:01.914 --> 29:03.480
Let this serve as a reminder

29:03.611 --> 29:06.527
that only you
can tell your story.

29:07.746 --> 29:09.486
May I?

29:09.617 --> 29:12.838
[cheers and applause]

29:12.968 --> 29:15.841
[uplifting music plays]

29:15.971 --> 29:21.498
♪♪

29:21.629 --> 29:27.069
♪♪

29:27.200 --> 29:29.071
[film whirring]

29:29.202 --> 29:35.512
♪♪

29:35.643 --> 29:41.867
♪♪

29:41.997 --> 29:46.349
I want you all to support
this wonderful organization,

29:46.480 --> 29:49.048
because they alone
can get laws in the books

29:49.178 --> 29:50.397
to stop these lynchings.

29:50.527 --> 29:51.702
[crowd shouts in agreement]

29:51.833 --> 29:53.530
And they alone can see to it

29:53.661 --> 29:56.577
that what happened in that trial
doesn't happen again.

29:56.707 --> 29:58.274
[crowd shouts in agreement]

29:58.405 --> 30:01.364
We can't leave it
in their hands.

30:01.495 --> 30:03.497
Mississippi officials
have shown us

30:03.627 --> 30:08.328
that they cannot be trusted to
uphold the laws of this nation,

30:08.458 --> 30:11.374
a nation that my son's father,
Louis Till,

30:11.505 --> 30:13.855
died fighting to protect.

30:13.986 --> 30:15.726
[cheers and applause]

30:15.857 --> 30:17.685
[flashbulbs pop]

30:20.209 --> 30:22.908
REPORTER: On the day
that the verdict came down,

30:23.038 --> 30:27.913
our members and our leaders
were shocked and revolted

30:28.043 --> 30:30.959
by the fact that
the state of Mississippi

30:31.090 --> 30:35.137
had seen fit
to take two murderers

30:35.268 --> 30:37.357
and elevate them
to the level of heroes.

30:37.487 --> 30:40.403
The leadership of
the United States

30:40.534 --> 30:44.799
has definitely suffered
in Africa and in Europe

30:44.930 --> 30:46.845
because of what's happened
in Mississippi.

30:46.975 --> 30:50.631
The jury that was supposed
to render this verdict

30:50.761 --> 30:54.200
contained not a single member
of the race

30:54.330 --> 30:57.159
of the boy who had been killed.

30:57.290 --> 30:59.161
We will continue to battle
this thing

30:59.292 --> 31:02.904
until every man, woman,
and child of the United States,

31:03.035 --> 31:07.909
when he goes before a court
of justice, will get justice.

31:08.040 --> 31:09.737
[cheers and applause]

31:09.868 --> 31:13.959
Days ago, my son's lynchers
were bailed out of jail

31:14.089 --> 31:16.222
by a group of plantation owners

31:16.352 --> 31:19.138
who banded together
to raise $20,000...

31:19.268 --> 31:22.402
So that those men could get back
to supporting their families

31:22.532 --> 31:24.404
until the grand jury convenes.

31:24.534 --> 31:27.842
[crowd boos]

31:27.973 --> 31:30.192
We must do more than complain.

31:30.323 --> 31:31.585
[crowd shouts "yes"]

31:31.715 --> 31:34.631
We must band together,
just like them.

31:34.762 --> 31:37.460
We must use our anger
and our voices.

31:37.591 --> 31:41.638
And if our calls and letters
and telegrams are ignored...

31:41.769 --> 31:43.640
We must beat them
at their own game

31:43.771 --> 31:45.338
and protest the state of
Mississippi

31:45.468 --> 31:47.688
with our pocketbooks!

31:47.818 --> 31:50.647
[cheers and applause]

31:50.778 --> 31:53.476
[inspiring music plays]

31:53.607 --> 31:56.088
♪♪

32:33.386 --> 32:36.519
[solemn music plays]

32:36.650 --> 32:43.526
♪♪

32:43.657 --> 32:50.577
♪♪

32:50.707 --> 32:57.584
♪♪

32:57.714 --> 33:04.591
♪♪

33:04.721 --> 33:11.554
♪♪

33:11.685 --> 33:13.295
♪♪

33:13.426 --> 33:15.297
-ROY: Carolyn!
-[car horn honks]

33:15.428 --> 33:22.304
♪♪

33:22.435 --> 33:29.355
♪♪

33:29.485 --> 33:36.362
♪♪

33:36.492 --> 33:39.104
♪♪

33:39.234 --> 33:42.411
I just wanted to make sure
I got everything.

33:42.542 --> 33:43.586
♪♪

33:43.717 --> 33:45.632
Ain't like there's much to get.

33:45.762 --> 33:52.595
♪♪

33:52.726 --> 33:59.602
♪♪

33:59.733 --> 34:03.128
♪♪

34:03.258 --> 34:06.044
[indistinct conversations]

34:06.174 --> 34:09.830
The NAACP is using this woman
to collect huge sums of money

34:09.960 --> 34:12.006
based on distorted facts.

34:12.137 --> 34:13.442
She's a grieving mother.

34:13.573 --> 34:15.140
She's a puppet.

34:15.270 --> 34:17.229
The Northern papers are printing
her hate propaganda

34:17.359 --> 34:19.187
like it's gospel,
knowing damn well

34:19.318 --> 34:22.060
she's painting Mississippi
with a dangerous brush.

34:22.190 --> 34:25.846
"They're calling Mississippi
the purgatory of racial tension

34:25.976 --> 34:28.849
and a hellhole of
American democracy.

34:28.979 --> 34:31.982
How long are we gonna let them
get away with that?"

34:32.113 --> 34:33.810
"If Till was really killed,

34:33.941 --> 34:36.857
then the NAACP,
its mongrel leaders,

34:36.987 --> 34:39.860
and the abominable excuse
for a Supreme Court

34:39.990 --> 34:42.254
are solely responsible, not us."

34:42.384 --> 34:44.821
This is just today's mail.

34:44.952 --> 34:46.345
We need a rebuttal--

34:46.475 --> 34:49.217
a story powerful enough
to silence them

34:49.348 --> 34:51.480
so that our readers feel heard.

34:51.611 --> 34:53.569
What about the boy's father?

34:53.700 --> 34:56.224
What about him?
He's dead, right?

34:56.355 --> 34:58.792
A war hero, died overseas.
There's no story there.

34:58.922 --> 35:01.490
Senator Eastland seems to think
there's more to it than that.

35:01.621 --> 35:03.797
It's time we did
a little digging.

35:05.320 --> 35:09.455
Packton, you were hot on this
back in September.

35:09.585 --> 35:11.892
You go ahead and take the lead.

35:13.981 --> 35:15.548
I'll meet you in D.C.

35:15.678 --> 35:17.202
From there, we'll head to
Grand Rapids

35:17.332 --> 35:19.029
and then Des Moines.

35:19.160 --> 35:21.423
Well, I suppose I should be
grateful to get a few days

35:21.554 --> 35:25.601
to rest and recharge in Chicago
with Gene and Mama.

35:25.732 --> 35:27.342
I'm exhausted
just thinking about it.

35:27.473 --> 35:30.606
I know it's been tough,
but these next few weeks

35:30.737 --> 35:34.088
before the grand jury convenes
are critical,

35:34.219 --> 35:37.918
and while you're home,
you need to talk to a lawyer

35:38.048 --> 35:39.441
so we can start negotiating.

35:39.572 --> 35:42.270
I am not looking to get rich
off of any tour.

35:42.401 --> 35:43.532
I just want to pay my rent.

35:43.663 --> 35:45.099
WILKINS:
Good afternoon.

35:45.230 --> 35:48.146
Roy.
What brings you down here?

35:48.276 --> 35:50.931
This.

35:51.061 --> 35:56.806
♪♪

35:56.937 --> 35:59.548
-How much did you know?
-Please, Mr. Wilkins.

35:59.679 --> 36:02.029
I learned about Louis' death
by telegram 10 years ago.

36:02.160 --> 36:03.465
And what did it say?

36:03.596 --> 36:05.467
I-It said he--
he was charged with

36:05.598 --> 36:07.426
willful misconduct in Italy.

36:07.556 --> 36:09.906
And what did that mean to you--
"willful misconduct?"

36:10.037 --> 36:12.518
-I didn't know.
-He was executed!

36:13.649 --> 36:16.348
Hanged for rape, Mamie.

36:16.478 --> 36:18.741
And by you leaving that detail
out of your speeches,

36:18.872 --> 36:20.265
people are saying
that you implied

36:20.395 --> 36:22.919
that he died
for our country in war.

36:23.050 --> 36:25.661
[groans]

36:25.792 --> 36:29.752
I didn't believe it, all right?

36:29.883 --> 36:31.928
This country isn't the only
place where they [sniffles]

36:32.059 --> 36:34.104
lynch Black men
for looking at white women.

36:34.235 --> 36:36.281
-But you have no proof.
-Neither did they!

36:36.411 --> 36:40.110
♪♪

36:40.241 --> 36:42.287
Louis Till was a bad husband.

36:42.417 --> 36:44.854
He stepped out.
He put his hands on me.

36:44.985 --> 36:47.117
I am not proud of any of that.

36:47.248 --> 36:51.121
I-I am ashamed, but that
has nothing to do with Emmett.

36:51.252 --> 36:52.906
He barely knew his father.

36:53.036 --> 36:55.300
He-- He didn't learn a thing
from that man.

36:55.430 --> 36:57.171
♪♪

36:57.302 --> 36:59.347
"Like father, like son."

36:59.478 --> 37:02.742
♪♪

37:02.872 --> 37:05.353
It is no coincidence
that this story came out

37:05.484 --> 37:07.616
right before the grand jury
hearing, is it?

37:07.747 --> 37:11.141
If I had known, Mamie, I could
have gotten ahead of this thing.

37:13.883 --> 37:16.277
I cannot let that
poison the jury.

37:16.408 --> 37:18.888
I-I-- I-I have to fight this.

37:19.019 --> 37:21.239
Unfortunately,
you don't have much time.

37:21.369 --> 37:26.200
If you want the last word,
you must control the message.

37:26.331 --> 37:27.854
Let us help you do that.

37:27.984 --> 37:29.725
Mamie's exhausted.

37:29.856 --> 37:32.075
If you want her to continue
for you,

37:32.206 --> 37:34.861
she deserves a substantial
piece of the tour.

37:34.991 --> 37:36.254
That's our bottom line.

37:36.384 --> 37:38.081
Enough!

37:38.212 --> 37:40.214
I can't do this right now.

37:40.345 --> 37:42.260
Not while they're saying
these sick things about my boy.

37:42.390 --> 37:46.307
I am sorry, but I need to go.

37:46.438 --> 37:48.266
-Mamie.
-Thank you...

37:48.396 --> 37:50.616
for everything you've done,
both of you,

37:50.746 --> 37:52.966
but I need to be alone.

37:53.096 --> 37:58.537
♪♪

37:58.667 --> 38:00.321
♪♪

38:00.452 --> 38:03.324
Well, now, they haven't [sighs]
said a word about that night

38:03.455 --> 38:05.587
to anybody but me,

38:05.718 --> 38:09.069
so why should they tell
some fiction writer?

38:09.199 --> 38:11.289
[chuckles]

38:13.291 --> 38:14.640
I'll pay.

38:14.770 --> 38:17.382
How much?

38:17.512 --> 38:19.297
$4,000,

38:19.427 --> 38:20.863
to be divided
among the three of you.

38:20.994 --> 38:22.256
Now, Mr. Breland, of course,

38:22.387 --> 38:24.302
will receive his commission.

38:24.432 --> 38:25.607
In addition to your advance,

38:26.042 --> 38:28.436
LOOKmagazine will add
a percentage of the profits

38:28.567 --> 38:30.177
from the publication
of the story.

38:30.308 --> 38:31.744
Mm-hmm.

38:31.874 --> 38:33.267
ROY:
I don't know, J.W.

38:33.398 --> 38:35.269
I ain't feeling right
about all this.

38:35.400 --> 38:36.836
MILAM:
Oh, really?

38:36.966 --> 38:38.968
You feeling right about
your market being closed?

38:39.012 --> 38:41.319
Or how y'all feeling
about not being able

38:41.449 --> 38:42.755
to put food
in your boys' mouths

38:42.885 --> 38:44.017
'cause everybody jumped ship?

38:45.714 --> 38:47.847
[sighs]

38:47.977 --> 38:49.892
What would we have to do?

38:50.023 --> 38:51.372
Confess.

38:51.503 --> 38:53.200
[sighs]

38:56.769 --> 38:59.249
I will make no claim
that the story

38:59.380 --> 39:01.774
is based on a confession
from the actual killers,

39:01.904 --> 39:04.907
but rather from
very reliable sources.

39:05.038 --> 39:05.995
Mm.

39:06.387 --> 39:09.085
Now, this story will be billed
as my version

39:09.216 --> 39:10.739
of exactly what happened--

39:10.870 --> 39:13.307
exactly what was said,
exactly what was done

39:13.438 --> 39:15.788
at exactly what date
and what hour.

39:15.918 --> 39:18.791
But I will not state,
declare, or claim

39:18.921 --> 39:21.663
that I had the assistance
of any particular person.

39:23.143 --> 39:24.884
And what happens
if they get indicted

39:25.014 --> 39:27.365
on them kidnapping charges
in the coming days?

39:27.495 --> 39:28.627
Well, if there's a trial,

39:28.757 --> 39:29.932
the magazine won't publish
the story

39:30.063 --> 39:31.456
until there's a verdict,

39:31.586 --> 39:34.110
but I don't want to
wait for all that.

39:34.241 --> 39:37.070
Once you sign that contract,
we begin,

39:37.200 --> 39:39.638
and we'll need to keep
our meetings quiet.

39:39.768 --> 39:41.291
I don't see any reason
why anybody should know

39:41.422 --> 39:43.337
what's being discussed
in this office.

39:43.468 --> 39:46.166
And even if we meet in secret,
things happen.

39:46.296 --> 39:48.473
People talk. What then?

39:48.603 --> 39:51.345
If I'm subpoenaed
for some reason,

39:51.476 --> 39:53.782
I will invoke
my constitutional right

39:53.913 --> 39:55.131
to withhold my sources.

39:57.351 --> 39:58.918
I'll refuse to testify.

40:01.268 --> 40:04.010
So, we have a deal?

40:04.140 --> 40:07.143
[tense music plays]

40:07.274 --> 40:13.759
♪♪

40:16.283 --> 40:18.067
Well, if it isn't
my favorite Yankee,

40:18.198 --> 40:19.808
Mr. Dan Wakefield.

40:20.635 --> 40:22.507
I guess Strider's deputies
are gonna have to try

40:22.637 --> 40:24.117
a little harder to keep you
out of the Delta, huh?

40:24.247 --> 40:26.293
I guess so, yeah. [chuckles]

40:26.424 --> 40:28.861
What a piss-poor turnout.

40:30.079 --> 40:31.603
Yeah, well, this case is bigger
than any courthouse,

40:31.733 --> 40:34.301
but you know
that firsthand, don't you?

40:34.736 --> 40:36.869
What's eating at you?

40:37.478 --> 40:39.219
Before the murder trial,

40:39.349 --> 40:41.308
the case was all about
a wolf-whistle.

40:41.439 --> 40:44.006
Once the press got wind
of Carolyn Bryant's testimony,

40:44.050 --> 40:47.401
it turned into something else--
attempted rape.

40:47.532 --> 40:49.185
The story about his father
really ties it all together,

40:49.316 --> 40:50.796
-doesn't it?
-Now, listen--

40:50.926 --> 40:52.667
Your paper justified
the boy's murder.

40:54.016 --> 40:55.540
We just reported the facts,

40:55.670 --> 40:58.586
and we did so with an editorial
assuring readers

40:58.717 --> 41:00.545
that the details of
Till's father's execution

41:00.675 --> 41:02.590
had no bearing
on this kidnapping case.

41:02.721 --> 41:04.853
[door opens]

41:07.465 --> 41:08.770
I guess you're about to find out

41:08.901 --> 41:10.511
if any of that's true,
aren't you?

41:12.774 --> 41:14.776
COURT CLERK: The grand jury
has reached decisions

41:14.907 --> 41:18.214
in all of the cases
under consideration.

41:18.345 --> 41:19.999
It's over.

41:20.956 --> 41:22.349
No trial.

41:24.133 --> 41:25.526
They're free.

41:26.658 --> 41:27.833
No.

41:27.963 --> 41:29.095
Don't leave the shop, Gene.

41:29.225 --> 41:31.140
I-I-I'm fine.

41:32.098 --> 41:33.839
Call Mama, will you?

41:34.796 --> 41:36.624
I can't bear it.

41:44.502 --> 41:46.068
[receiver clacks]

41:50.551 --> 41:53.946
[telephone rings]

41:58.298 --> 42:00.474
[receiver clatters]

42:00.605 --> 42:03.477
[somber music plays]

42:03.608 --> 42:10.440
♪♪

42:10.571 --> 42:17.447
♪♪

42:17.578 --> 42:24.454
♪♪

42:24.585 --> 42:31.505
♪♪

42:31.636 --> 42:36.684
♪♪

42:36.815 --> 42:39.905
[wringer whirring]

42:40.035 --> 42:45.301
♪♪

42:45.432 --> 42:46.868
[whirring stops]

42:46.999 --> 42:48.914
♪♪

42:49.044 --> 42:51.046
[switch clicking]

42:51.177 --> 42:56.661
♪♪

42:56.791 --> 42:59.707
[grunts]

42:59.838 --> 43:04.103
♪♪

43:04.233 --> 43:06.496
Emmett!

43:06.627 --> 43:08.673
[sobbing]

43:08.803 --> 43:15.027
♪♪

43:15.157 --> 43:21.381
♪♪

43:21.511 --> 43:24.602
[sobbing continues]

43:24.732 --> 43:26.212
♪♪

43:26.342 --> 43:27.779
[door opens]

43:27.909 --> 43:29.694
♪♪

43:29.824 --> 43:31.347
[door closes]

43:31.478 --> 43:37.005
♪♪

43:37.136 --> 43:42.707
♪♪

43:42.837 --> 43:44.839
[sobs, sniffles]

43:51.846 --> 43:54.980
I've been calling, baby.

43:55.110 --> 43:57.069
Everybody has.

43:59.332 --> 44:01.813
I am so sorry.

44:06.731 --> 44:09.081
Washing machine's broke, Mama.

44:10.517 --> 44:12.954
Okay.

44:12.998 --> 44:14.434
Then we'll fix it.

44:14.564 --> 44:18.046
Emmett was always doing laundry.

44:18.177 --> 44:21.789
He had to have his clothes
just so.

44:21.920 --> 44:24.139
That boy had too much pride
for his own good.

44:24.270 --> 44:26.141
-Stop that.
-No, Mama. Don't you see?

44:26.272 --> 44:28.187
He went and broke
the damn machine before he left,

44:28.317 --> 44:30.189
and he kept it from me.

44:30.319 --> 44:32.017
What you mean he broke it?

44:33.845 --> 44:36.064
You haven't done laundry
in two months?

44:36.195 --> 44:38.458
I was never home long enough.

44:38.588 --> 44:41.026
Oh.

44:41.156 --> 44:43.942
[clicking]

44:46.118 --> 44:48.642
[sighs, sniffles]

44:52.733 --> 44:54.430
[clinking]

44:54.561 --> 44:57.346
[washing machine whirring]

44:59.697 --> 45:02.438
[switch clicks, whirring stops]

45:02.569 --> 45:06.355
Just needed to give it
a-a little TLC.

45:06.486 --> 45:09.532
You always swoop in
to save the day, don't you?

45:10.925 --> 45:14.015
On a day like today,

45:14.146 --> 45:16.104
I wish that I could.

45:17.018 --> 45:20.021
I just don't know how I'm gonna
get through the holidays.

45:20.152 --> 45:22.676
[sighs]

45:22.807 --> 45:26.811
[voice breaking] It'll be our
first Thanksgiving without him.

45:27.637 --> 45:31.859
Meanwhile, those men are free
to carve their turkeys

45:31.990 --> 45:35.733
and watch their boys open
presents on Christmas morning.

45:37.343 --> 45:41.521
When I think of that,
when I think of--

45:41.651 --> 45:44.480
of all that I'll miss,

45:44.611 --> 45:47.701
of all that
they've taken from me,

45:47.832 --> 45:49.050
I can't help but wonder

45:49.181 --> 45:51.270
what more I could've done
to see to it

45:51.400 --> 45:53.272
that they paid
for what they did.

45:53.402 --> 45:54.534
Unh-unh.

45:54.664 --> 45:56.492
[crying]

45:56.623 --> 45:58.886
God'll see to it.

45:59.017 --> 46:02.107
I-I should've fought harder.

46:02.237 --> 46:04.326
I-I could've been louder
than those articles

46:04.457 --> 46:06.328
about his father, and...

46:07.634 --> 46:11.333
You did more than most women

46:11.464 --> 46:14.902
could have done
in your position.

46:15.033 --> 46:19.864
Most women would have taken
to their bed for months--

46:19.994 --> 46:22.083
for years--

46:22.214 --> 46:24.085
and they would've had
every right

46:24.216 --> 46:26.131
to have done just that.

46:27.959 --> 46:29.699
What if I had been-- been--

46:29.830 --> 46:32.006
been harder on him,
like you were with me?

46:32.137 --> 46:34.313
M-Maybe he--
he would still be here.

46:34.443 --> 46:36.315
Enough.

46:38.186 --> 46:40.362
That woman--

46:40.493 --> 46:43.148
those monsters--

46:43.278 --> 46:45.063
they poisoned the jury.

46:45.193 --> 46:46.412
[sniffles]

46:46.542 --> 46:49.328
Don't let them get
inside your head, too.

46:49.458 --> 46:52.374
[sobs] But I can't get them out.

46:52.505 --> 46:55.160
-I--
-You got to try, because--

46:55.290 --> 46:59.425
because there are things
we'll never know.

46:59.555 --> 47:05.344
♪♪

47:05.474 --> 47:07.912
Like what really happened
to him.

47:08.042 --> 47:13.743
♪♪

47:13.874 --> 47:19.358
They took his body,
not his spirit.

47:19.488 --> 47:23.971
♪♪

47:24.102 --> 47:28.846
His death woke up the world,
Mamie.

47:28.976 --> 47:30.804
♪♪

47:30.935 --> 47:35.200
But I never wanted him
to be a martyr, Mama.

47:35.330 --> 47:36.854
[crying] I know.

47:36.984 --> 47:38.159
I-I never--

47:38.290 --> 47:40.640
No, no, no, no.

47:40.770 --> 47:45.384
I never wanted that.

47:45.514 --> 47:52.260
♪♪

47:52.391 --> 47:59.224
♪♪

48:00.529 --> 48:02.401
To freedom.

48:02.531 --> 48:04.098
-Freedom.
-To freedom.

48:04.229 --> 48:06.884
-[glasses clink]
-All right.

48:07.014 --> 48:09.277
Well, a-all right, al--
all right, all right.

48:09.408 --> 48:11.453
Let's take it easy
on the swill, now.

48:11.584 --> 48:13.629
I need you
thinking straight.

48:13.760 --> 48:15.022
Straight as I'll ever be.

48:15.153 --> 48:17.459
[chuckling] Okay.

48:17.590 --> 48:19.461
So, I'd like to
start by, uh,

48:19.592 --> 48:21.986
clearing up a rumor
that's been eating up

48:22.116 --> 48:23.726
a lot of folks' time
since all this began.

48:23.857 --> 48:24.814
Hmm.

48:25.032 --> 48:27.208
Now, you had at least
two white men

48:27.339 --> 48:28.775
and three Negroes
with you all that night,

48:28.906 --> 48:30.603
-and I want their names.
-No, we were alone.

48:30.733 --> 48:31.909
You even think about
printing anything else,

48:32.039 --> 48:33.345
I'll tear that contract
up right now.

48:33.736 --> 48:35.651
Don't act like you don't know
about the double jeopardy law.

48:35.782 --> 48:38.654
These boys can't be tried again,
even with a confession,

48:38.785 --> 48:40.265
but if they incriminate
someone else,

48:40.395 --> 48:43.181
charges could be brought
against those parties.

48:43.311 --> 48:46.488
Of course. Of course.

48:46.619 --> 48:48.534
Y'all can't blame me
for digging, now, can you?

48:48.664 --> 48:50.710
[chuckles] All right.

48:50.840 --> 48:55.715
Uh, so, I want to start with,
uh, the night you took Emmett

48:55.845 --> 48:57.108
from Mose Wright's home.

48:57.238 --> 49:01.460
It was, uh, August 28th of 1955,
correct?

49:01.590 --> 49:03.288
Yeah.

49:03.418 --> 49:04.898
What sent you there?

49:09.163 --> 49:13.428
My brother and me had heard
that this Chicago nigger

49:13.559 --> 49:17.693
had gotten mouthy,
whistled at my sister-in-law.

49:17.824 --> 49:20.261
One of my workers said
that he was staying

49:20.392 --> 49:22.046
with the old preacher,

49:22.176 --> 49:25.658
and so, we drove out to
Mose Wright's and asked for him,

49:25.788 --> 49:27.486
and the preacher led us
right to him.

49:28.400 --> 49:30.532
[thud]

49:30.663 --> 49:32.491
-Please.
-You want out of this?

49:32.621 --> 49:34.928
Stay down
and shut the hell up.

49:35.059 --> 49:36.974
[engine rumbles]

49:37.104 --> 49:40.716
[vehicle departs]

49:40.847 --> 49:47.506
♪♪

49:47.636 --> 49:50.030
So, when you got him,

49:50.161 --> 49:52.076
did you take him
back to, uh, the market

49:52.206 --> 49:54.295
for Mrs. Bryant to identify?

49:54.426 --> 49:59.518
♪♪

49:59.648 --> 50:01.999
-J.W.?
-Yeah?

50:02.129 --> 50:03.522
You take him back to the market?

50:03.652 --> 50:05.176
No.

50:05.306 --> 50:06.699
Well, no reason to.

50:06.829 --> 50:07.917
He didn't deny he was the one
done the talking,

50:08.048 --> 50:10.007
so we didn't need her.
We knew.

50:10.137 --> 50:11.573
We knew.

50:11.704 --> 50:14.794
[doors open, close]

50:17.710 --> 50:20.147
[engine revs]

50:20.278 --> 50:26.197
♪♪

50:26.327 --> 50:29.722
♪♪

50:29.852 --> 50:33.117
After we left the uncle's,
we just went driving,

50:33.247 --> 50:36.163
looking for a spot just to
scare some sense into the boy.

50:36.294 --> 50:39.253
♪♪

50:39.384 --> 50:41.560
Here he is.

50:41.690 --> 50:42.996
The smart talker.

50:43.127 --> 50:44.824
ROY:
Well, now, looky here.

50:44.954 --> 50:46.869
Ain't saying much now,
boy, are you?

50:47.000 --> 50:48.828
[whimpering]

50:48.958 --> 50:55.008
♪♪

50:55.139 --> 50:56.488
[liquid pouring]

50:56.618 --> 50:58.055
Ahh.

51:00.622 --> 51:02.102
Go.

51:02.233 --> 51:05.149
♪♪

51:05.279 --> 51:07.629
Come on. Go on.

51:07.760 --> 51:13.244
♪♪

51:13.374 --> 51:15.811
[whimpering]

51:18.205 --> 51:21.208
What kinda poison
they pumping in you up north

51:21.339 --> 51:23.993
to make you think it's okay
to run your filthy mouth

51:24.124 --> 51:25.343
to my wife?

51:25.473 --> 51:27.997
[screams, crying]

51:28.128 --> 51:29.608
MILAM:
He was tough.

51:29.738 --> 51:31.436
We never could scare him enough.

51:31.566 --> 51:34.482
Throughout the whole ordeal,
he never even hollered.

51:34.613 --> 51:37.616
[punches landing,
Emmett screaming]

51:37.746 --> 51:41.663
♪♪

51:41.794 --> 51:44.057
We drove around with him in
the back of the truck for hours.

51:44.188 --> 51:46.190
He never even tried to run.

51:46.320 --> 51:47.800
♪♪

51:47.930 --> 51:50.411
All right, get him out.
Come on!

51:50.542 --> 51:52.935
If folks haven't already started
looking for him, they will.

51:53.066 --> 51:54.154
Well, why the hell
did you bring him here?

51:54.285 --> 51:55.373
We got lost.

51:55.938 --> 51:57.853
Well, I got fields to work,
I got farmhands gonna show up.

51:57.984 --> 51:59.333
Take care of it.

51:59.464 --> 52:03.859
♪♪

52:03.990 --> 52:08.255
The boy was hopeless,
so we took him back to my place.

52:08.386 --> 52:10.344
And that's where we whipped him.

52:10.475 --> 52:12.825
[whip cracking,
Emmett screaming]

52:12.955 --> 52:15.088
[door squeaks]

52:15.219 --> 52:21.312
♪♪

52:21.442 --> 52:22.878
♪♪

52:23.009 --> 52:25.272
HUIE: The farmhands, uh,
said they saw you

52:25.403 --> 52:28.449
with the boy at a plantation
run by your brother, Leslie.

52:28.580 --> 52:30.451
No, we were at my shop,
like I just said to you.

52:30.582 --> 52:32.497
♪♪

52:32.627 --> 52:33.846
-Okay.
-Okay.

52:33.976 --> 52:35.674
All right.

52:35.804 --> 52:38.372
[whip cracking,
Emmett screaming]

52:38.503 --> 52:43.899
♪♪

52:44.030 --> 52:46.293
MILAM: He just kept saying
he wasn't afraid of us.

52:48.165 --> 52:51.690
Kept saying he was
as good as us.

52:51.820 --> 52:53.300
Just taunting us.

52:53.431 --> 52:55.563
Even said that he had
white women.

52:55.694 --> 52:57.478
♪♪

52:57.609 --> 52:59.263
[gun clicks]

52:59.393 --> 53:01.830
[weakly] Mama.

53:02.657 --> 53:04.659
[gunshot]

53:11.536 --> 53:13.015
Uh...

53:13.146 --> 53:15.192
So you-- you whipped him
good at your place.

53:15.322 --> 53:16.323
Then what?

53:18.195 --> 53:19.718
We got back in my truck.

53:19.848 --> 53:21.633
HUIE:
Could the boy walk on his own?

53:22.808 --> 53:24.070
Yeah. Sure.

53:25.202 --> 53:27.291
Was he bleeding?

53:27.421 --> 53:28.770
MILAM:
Not much.

53:28.901 --> 53:31.686
Pistol-whipping bruises
more than it cuts.

53:31.817 --> 53:34.298
-So, you left your shop...
-Mm-hmm.

53:34.428 --> 53:36.561
And we went to
Progressive Ginning Company.

53:36.691 --> 53:38.302
We took an old gin fan

53:38.432 --> 53:41.261
and made the boy load it up
on the back of the truck,

53:41.392 --> 53:44.221
and then we drove off
looking for that bluff.

53:44.351 --> 53:47.006
We were hell-bent
on finding that.

53:47.136 --> 53:48.616
Was he alive
when y'all got there?

53:50.401 --> 53:52.490
Yeah.

53:55.406 --> 53:57.146
That's where we made him
undress.

53:57.277 --> 53:58.974
♪♪

53:59.105 --> 54:00.672
He didn't like that.

54:00.802 --> 54:02.064
[both grunting]

54:02.195 --> 54:03.544
And after,
we just kind of stood there

54:03.675 --> 54:06.199
for a little while,
just hating each other.

54:06.330 --> 54:08.201
♪♪

54:08.332 --> 54:11.160
All right, get the fan.

54:11.291 --> 54:12.814
And then I gave him a chance
to fix things.

54:12.945 --> 54:15.991
I said, "You still had
white women?"

54:16.122 --> 54:19.386
♪♪

54:19.517 --> 54:21.258
He said, "Yeah."

54:21.388 --> 54:24.826
♪♪

54:24.957 --> 54:27.394
So, I stood there
and listened to him

54:27.525 --> 54:29.614
throw that poison at me,
and I just made up my mind.

54:29.744 --> 54:33.008
I was gonna make an example
out of him.

54:33.139 --> 54:36.621
♪♪

54:36.751 --> 54:38.318
So I shot him.

54:38.449 --> 54:40.842
♪♪

54:40.973 --> 54:44.063
Ready? One, two, three!

54:44.193 --> 54:45.804
[groans]

54:45.934 --> 54:48.110
One, two, three.

54:48.894 --> 54:51.113
[splash]

54:51.244 --> 54:53.072
[water bubbles]

54:53.202 --> 54:54.639
[panting]

54:54.769 --> 54:59.470
♪♪

55:00.601 --> 55:02.647
ANNOUNCER: Headlines screamed
across the nation,

55:02.777 --> 55:04.431
millions of words
were written about it,

55:04.562 --> 55:07.216
a trial would be held,
yet the truth about

55:07.347 --> 55:09.088
the Emmett Till killing
in Mississippi

55:09.218 --> 55:11.264
remained hidden until now.

55:11.395 --> 55:13.048
The brutal step-by-step account

55:13.179 --> 55:15.442
of what happened on
that fateful night.

55:15.573 --> 55:17.705
Get your copy ofLOOK early.

55:17.836 --> 55:20.665
[somber music plays]

55:20.795 --> 55:27.672
♪♪

55:27.802 --> 55:29.630
♪♪

55:29.761 --> 55:33.242
I don't know how much more
I can stand.

55:33.373 --> 55:35.244
How I can go on.

55:37.159 --> 55:39.858
These horrible lies they tell
to explain away

55:39.988 --> 55:42.904
the killing of a child
in cold blood--

55:43.035 --> 55:46.952
a child that they portrayed
as a man--

55:47.082 --> 55:48.910
a man who never fought back
and who-- who--

55:49.041 --> 55:51.086
who was defiant until the end.

55:51.217 --> 55:53.045
They-- They aren't human.
They're beasts.

55:54.786 --> 55:56.483
And that woman--

55:56.614 --> 55:59.268
I don't even see
how she can sleep at night.

56:05.362 --> 56:09.366
I used to think there was
a reason for all this pain--

56:11.193 --> 56:14.893
that God had given me
a purpose and a mission,

56:15.023 --> 56:16.721
and I was happy to accept it

56:16.851 --> 56:20.115
when I thought that people were
listening, but here we are.

56:20.246 --> 56:23.510
Some white man just put his name
on that, and that is it.

56:23.641 --> 56:25.164
End of story!

56:25.294 --> 56:27.035
It's only the end if you say so.

56:27.166 --> 56:29.951
What can I say now?

56:30.082 --> 56:33.520
Nothing I have said or ever
will say is going to matter,

56:33.651 --> 56:37.742
because that trash
is now my son's legacy!

56:37.872 --> 56:40.527
And the sick thing is,
if it weren't for this article,

56:40.658 --> 56:42.703
people would have
forgotten about Emmett.

56:42.834 --> 56:44.270
-Well, that's not true.
-Open a paper.

56:44.401 --> 56:46.707
Turn on a television.
Emmett is old news now.

56:46.838 --> 56:48.317
People are thinking
about what's next.

56:48.448 --> 56:49.710
GENE: Come on, now.
That's not true, Mamie.

56:49.841 --> 56:51.582
But it is!

56:53.061 --> 56:55.412
I used to be a part
of the movement.

56:57.022 --> 56:59.328
Now I am just sitting at home,
watching it unfold,

56:59.459 --> 57:01.200
while folks like
Martin Luther King

57:01.330 --> 57:04.421
and Rosa Parks are out there
making things happen.

57:06.858 --> 57:09.469
I don't expect for you
to understand.

57:12.298 --> 57:14.039
But I do.

57:17.303 --> 57:20.393
You feel...

57:20.524 --> 57:22.221
left behind.

57:22.351 --> 57:24.310
♪♪

57:24.441 --> 57:27.792
And you're full of regrets--

57:27.922 --> 57:32.405
of all the things you wish
you had said but couldn't.

57:32.536 --> 57:34.799
You couldn't...

57:34.929 --> 57:36.583
because you didn't know.

57:37.802 --> 57:40.935
Just like I couldn't have known
that I'd never get the chance

57:41.066 --> 57:42.676
to try to be the father
he deserved.

57:42.807 --> 57:44.983
Oh, I can't do this right now.

57:45.113 --> 57:47.028
I can't take it,
your-- your tenderness

57:47.159 --> 57:48.421
and-- and your kind words.

57:48.552 --> 57:49.857
I am just not in the right mind.

57:49.988 --> 57:54.035
Be angry, but do it with me.

57:54.166 --> 57:55.559
Marry me.

57:56.168 --> 57:57.430
Ridiculous.

57:59.301 --> 58:01.739
What, you call that a proposal?

58:01.869 --> 58:03.610
♪♪

58:03.741 --> 58:04.916
How is it any more ridiculous

58:05.046 --> 58:06.613
than all the other times
I've done it?

58:08.485 --> 58:09.660
You remember when I asked you
to marry me

58:09.790 --> 58:12.227
at the dinner table
last summer?

58:12.358 --> 58:14.578
Mose was there.

58:14.708 --> 58:16.014
Alma, too.

58:16.144 --> 58:18.146
And Emmett.

58:18.277 --> 58:25.153
♪♪

58:25.284 --> 58:31.856
♪♪

58:31.986 --> 58:38.253
♪♪

58:38.384 --> 58:39.516
♪♪

58:39.646 --> 58:41.343
He was my protector.

58:41.474 --> 58:44.346
♪♪

58:44.477 --> 58:47.045
And I wasn't there for him
when he needed me most.

58:47.175 --> 58:48.481
♪♪

58:48.612 --> 58:49.917
Well, I don't think
he'd want you stuck.

58:52.180 --> 58:53.704
I think he'd want you
to move forward.

58:53.834 --> 58:56.489
And I'm not just talking
about with me.

58:56.620 --> 59:02.103
Your words sparked
the whole world to fight.

59:02.234 --> 59:05.498
But right now, it's not
the world who needs that spark.

59:05.629 --> 59:06.543
It's you.

59:06.673 --> 59:09.633
♪♪

59:09.763 --> 59:11.548
I want it back.

59:11.678 --> 59:13.680
♪♪

59:13.811 --> 59:15.247
That spark.

59:15.377 --> 59:17.858
Then get out there and find it.

59:17.989 --> 59:21.122
[brakes squeal nearby]

59:21.253 --> 59:26.954
♪♪

59:27.085 --> 59:31.611
♪♪

59:31.742 --> 59:34.701
[indistinct chatter]

59:34.832 --> 59:41.708
♪♪

59:41.839 --> 59:48.497
♪♪

59:48.628 --> 59:51.065
I've been living in the moment
for too long.

59:53.807 --> 59:57.419
Maybe it's time
I focus on what's next.

59:57.550 --> 59:58.986
Mm-hmm.

59:59.117 --> 1:00:00.945
There it is.

1:00:01.075 --> 1:00:02.337
That spark.

1:00:04.470 --> 1:00:07.429
A-Ask me again.

1:00:08.866 --> 1:00:09.997
What?

1:00:13.174 --> 1:00:16.656
That ridiculous question
of yours.

1:00:22.183 --> 1:00:28.537
♪♪

1:00:28.668 --> 1:00:30.365
What was it again?

1:00:31.758 --> 1:00:33.151
[both laugh]

1:00:33.281 --> 1:00:39.200
♪♪

1:00:39.331 --> 1:00:42.203
♪♪

1:00:42.334 --> 1:00:43.814
Will you marry me?

1:00:43.944 --> 1:00:46.599
♪♪

1:00:46.730 --> 1:00:47.818
Mm-hmm.

1:00:47.948 --> 1:00:50.472
[laughter]

1:00:50.603 --> 1:00:52.649
♪♪

1:00:52.779 --> 1:00:53.998
[sighs]

1:00:54.041 --> 1:01:00.961
♪♪

1:01:01.092 --> 1:01:07.968
♪♪

1:01:08.099 --> 1:01:09.709
♪♪

1:01:09.840 --> 1:01:12.756
[indistinct conversations]

1:01:12.886 --> 1:01:19.806
♪♪

1:01:19.937 --> 1:01:26.813
♪♪

1:01:26.944 --> 1:01:33.820
♪♪

1:01:33.951 --> 1:01:40.261
♪♪

1:01:40.392 --> 1:01:41.785
Mrs. Bradley?

1:01:41.915 --> 1:01:43.700
It's an honor. I'm Rita.

1:01:43.830 --> 1:01:46.354
Oh, calling me Mamie's
just fine.

1:01:46.485 --> 1:01:47.616
It's nice to meet you.

1:01:47.747 --> 1:01:49.706
I remember my mama
skipping work

1:01:49.836 --> 1:01:52.317
to get in line
for your son's viewing.

1:01:52.447 --> 1:01:55.886
When she got home that night,
she just... held me.

1:01:56.016 --> 1:01:58.584
She was saying how brave
you were,

1:01:58.715 --> 1:02:00.064
how things were gonna
start changing

1:02:00.194 --> 1:02:01.848
because of what you did.

1:02:01.979 --> 1:02:03.937
She was right.

1:02:04.068 --> 1:02:10.944
♪♪

1:02:11.075 --> 1:02:17.908
♪♪

1:02:18.038 --> 1:02:22.042
♪♪

1:02:22.173 --> 1:02:25.045
MAMIE: When you find out
that you're gonna be a mother,

1:02:25.176 --> 1:02:27.047
you have all these ideas
in your head

1:02:27.178 --> 1:02:29.267
about how your baby's
gonna look

1:02:29.397 --> 1:02:31.791
and who he's gonna be.

1:02:31.922 --> 1:02:35.273
And then all of a sudden,
he's here,

1:02:35.403 --> 1:02:37.666
and none of that stuff
matters anymore

1:02:37.797 --> 1:02:42.976
because he decides
and you just let him be.

1:02:43.107 --> 1:02:45.892
NEWS ANCHOR:
On December 5, 1955,

1:02:46.023 --> 1:02:48.329
many of Montgomery's busses
were empty,

1:02:48.460 --> 1:02:50.767
the result of a Negro boycott
that began

1:02:50.897 --> 1:02:53.160
when Rosa Parks made
a momentous decision.

1:02:53.291 --> 1:02:55.336
I didn't feel that

1:02:55.467 --> 1:02:57.338
I was being treated
as a human being.

1:02:57.469 --> 1:02:58.905
I refused to give up
the seat.

1:02:59.036 --> 1:02:59.906
I said, "No."

1:03:00.037 --> 1:03:02.779
MAMIE: And then, when he falls,

1:03:02.909 --> 1:03:04.955
you blame yourself
for not being around enough,

1:03:05.085 --> 1:03:07.871
or for being around too much.

1:03:08.001 --> 1:03:09.873
And you can't help it.

1:03:10.003 --> 1:03:11.309
You're a mother.

1:03:11.439 --> 1:03:13.354
It's what we do.

1:03:13.485 --> 1:03:17.271
DR. KING: The year-old protest
is officially called off,

1:03:17.402 --> 1:03:19.883
and the Negro citizens
of Montgomery

1:03:20.013 --> 1:03:23.582
are urged to return
to the busses tomorrow morning

1:03:23.712 --> 1:03:25.366
on a non-segregated basis.

1:03:25.497 --> 1:03:27.760
[cheers and applause]

1:03:27.891 --> 1:03:29.414
MAMIE:
There will come a day

1:03:29.544 --> 1:03:32.156
when you'll be forced
to let go,

1:03:32.286 --> 1:03:34.723
and all you can do is hope
that you've done enough

1:03:34.854 --> 1:03:36.464
to prepare him for the world.

1:03:36.595 --> 1:03:38.597
REPORTER: ...Arkansas,
where nine Negro students

1:03:38.727 --> 1:03:40.164
were blocked
from entering the school

1:03:40.294 --> 1:03:41.861
by the National Guard.

1:03:41.992 --> 1:03:44.516
Today, on what marks
the 8-year anniversary

1:03:44.646 --> 1:03:47.345
of the death of Emmett Till,
Martin Luther King Jr.

1:03:47.475 --> 1:03:51.349
and nearly 250,000 people
from across the United States

1:03:51.479 --> 1:03:53.917
marched on Washington
for jobs and freedom.

1:03:54.047 --> 1:03:56.136
[crowd chanting "now!"]

1:03:56.267 --> 1:03:59.923
MAMIE: I thought I failed
to prepare you, Emmett.

1:04:00.053 --> 1:04:04.623
I tried to ignore it
for some time-- that blame--

1:04:04.753 --> 1:04:09.628
but it was always here,
buried deep in my bones.

1:04:09.758 --> 1:04:12.979
I kept myself busy, so I didn't
have to feel it.

1:04:13.110 --> 1:04:16.113
I'd just go, go, go because
I felt like

1:04:16.243 --> 1:04:19.638
I was part of something big.

1:04:19.768 --> 1:04:20.900
It was a great distraction...

1:04:21.031 --> 1:04:22.467
[TV turns off]

1:04:22.597 --> 1:04:26.166
...until I wasn't
part of anything at all.

1:04:26.297 --> 1:04:33.173
♪♪

1:04:33.304 --> 1:04:40.180
♪♪

1:04:40.311 --> 1:04:46.143
♪♪

1:04:46.273 --> 1:04:47.796
♪♪

1:04:47.927 --> 1:04:52.714
I had to sit in the stillness

1:04:52.845 --> 1:04:55.674
and feel my feelings,

1:04:55.804 --> 1:04:59.852
until the truth
finally revealed itself to me.

1:04:59.983 --> 1:05:03.377
I didn't fail to prepare you
for the world.

1:05:05.510 --> 1:05:07.468
The world failed you.

1:05:07.599 --> 1:05:09.427
♪♪

1:05:09.557 --> 1:05:12.821
It wasn't ready for you,
my boy.

1:05:12.952 --> 1:05:14.911
My Bobo.

1:05:16.086 --> 1:05:18.218
It still isn't.

1:05:18.349 --> 1:05:22.048
But I believe it will be,
one day.

1:05:23.745 --> 1:05:26.270
I have to believe...

1:05:26.400 --> 1:05:31.623
because of all the little boys
out there just like you.

1:05:31.753 --> 1:05:33.494
♪♪

1:05:33.625 --> 1:05:37.281
Boys whose mamas raised them
to live in a better world

1:05:37.411 --> 1:05:40.327
than the world
they were born into.

1:05:40.458 --> 1:05:43.330
[solemn music plays]

1:05:43.461 --> 1:05:50.294
♪♪

1:05:50.424 --> 1:05:57.301
♪♪

1:05:57.431 --> 1:06:04.308
♪♪

1:06:04.438 --> 1:06:08.399
♪♪

1:06:22.369 --> 1:06:24.110
I'm just glad it's over with.

1:06:24.241 --> 1:06:26.025
-REPORTER: Mrs. Bryant?
-I'm fine.

1:06:31.552 --> 1:06:33.772
I want to say that I feel that

1:06:33.902 --> 1:06:35.904
Emmett was more or less
loaned to me--

1:06:36.035 --> 1:06:37.776
that perhaps I wasn't his mother

1:06:37.906 --> 1:06:41.301
in the sense that other women
are mothers to their children,

1:06:41.432 --> 1:06:44.739
but I appreciate the 14 years
that we spent together.

1:06:44.870 --> 1:06:48.308
It was a joy watching
the unfolding of his mind

1:06:48.439 --> 1:06:50.745
and the development of his body,

1:06:50.876 --> 1:06:53.574
and I don't regret a minute of
the time that we spent together.

1:06:53.705 --> 1:06:55.837
I'm just sorry
that it was so short.

1:06:55.968 --> 1:06:58.449
♪♪
